I. game at Albany on Saturday must be apparent to all. A comparison of scores is evidence in itself that there must be no lack of cheering on that occasion if we expect to win. Regular leaders for rooting are all very well in their place, but without a crowd to make some noise, the purpose for which the leaders were appointed will hardly be carried out. Let every man feel it his duty to go to Albany Saturday and cheer the teatn on to victory. TEE CoNCORDIENSIS wishes it distinctly under- derstood that it is strictly unpartisan. In fact, we cannot remember when this publication has ever had occasion to refer to politics in any way. But in the present instance it has been thrust upon us. Since the metnorable night when the local ward nmninations were made, there has been a continuous :flood of campaign literature pouring in upon us. Desiring to get the gent1e1nan's views on the questions of the day, a reporter was sent to call, but the nominee absolutely refused to be interviewed and all the information we were able to obtain was that volunteered by the office boy, to the effect that \dere was tree oder gents inside and de boss was makin figgers on d' blackboard, t' explain how he'd git elected.\ LAST week we gave full particulars regarding a series of Saturday morning lectures which are open to the public. The subjects offered include Medireval History, Rhetoric and Style, Life and Monuments of Antiquity, Greek· Literature, and Life and Evolution of Living Forms. The methods employed will correspond very closely to those used in the University Extension lecture systetn. The formal lecture will be followed by open and informal discussion. Likewise, collateral read- ings will be required and a formal examination will be given to those who request it. A certificate of work done will be issued to those who follow a course of lectures and succeed in passing the final test. This action of the college authorities is highly comtnendable. It is distinctly a step in advance and deserves the patronage of the townspeople and the support of the whole college body. The time is past when the college and the university should be regarded as close corporations reserving their intellectual wares for the select few who have the good fortune to be associated with them as students. The college that does not extend its influence beyond its immediate bounds will be left behind by progressive institutions of learning. The college of today must do intellectual missionary work. University Extension lectures afford it an excellent opportunity to train secondary teachers in better educational n1ethods. The college will reap the reward, for better secondary work means better preparation for college.
